ral argument and a judge asks you, &quot;Well Atty So-and-so, have you read A vs. B?&quot;  and you havent read the case.  I have seen this happen (not to me thank god)--one time, the judge had even wrote the opinion.  So, not only do you need to know the cases in your brief inside and out, you need to know your opponents brief inside and out, not to mention reply briefs, as well as the judge's history, as well as any cases that may apply but you havent used, it goes on and on...<br><br>My point is not that my job is more difficult than a computer programmer's.  In fact, my job right now as a consultation atty is pretty lax and laid back.   <br><br>However, my REAL POINT is simply this:  The length of time it takes someone to do something is NO excuse for substandard and/or incomplete work, be it a brief or a computer game.   My clients expect me to do complete work, and I even have to pay for malpractice insurance in the event that some dodo head decides maybe my work was not so complete.  Using excuses concerning how difficult a job is or how much time it takes to complete it is a very American way of explaining away substandard work and incomplete products, and it is an excuse Im getting tired of hearing. =P<br><br>What avenue do paying customers of a computer game have for incomplete products?  Attorney General's offices that are already overworked and understaffed (and dealing with more important issues than a $45 game) and customer service departments *shudder* who dont do crap.  Sure, you can take the company to small claims, if you want to pay the $80 bucks to bring the action (which is twice as much as the game costs), plus take time off work for the hearing, yadda yadda yadda (and this doesnt include attorneys fees if you want to hire a lawyer).  IE, the only solution is not to buy the product, but in cases of games where you have already misled a fanbase and they have spent 2 years preparing for it...that doesnt seem like much of an option, now does it?<br><br>Your end result...computer stores continue to be flooded with games and other computer products that dont work as they should, as promised, or as intended.  Yet people pay for these products because well, this is the best they can get until something better comes along.  I think this is very sad and a bit disturbing, that is all.  It does not set a good example.<br><br><br><br> <p><b>Amberyll Arydunmorn </b><br><b>SHROUD WORLD</b><br>A NWN Persistent Campaign<br><i>Those who choose to walk in the path of the light shall never fear darkness.</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/usegalsoulsaver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Segal SoulSaver</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://wwp.icq.com/scripts/online.dll?icq=112539253&img=5" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lead-GM</span><br>  Posts: 3587<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(4/8/02 11:23:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lots of Discussion on saving Variables</span><hr size=1> I disagree. <p><b>Segal SoulSaver</b><br>Lead DM - <a href="http://Shroudworld.com">Shroud World</a> <BR>A NWN Persistent Campaign<BR><i>And so it was that the gods gifted upon mortal men the varied treasures and mankind was changed for the better and worse, but forever changed. </i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/uamberyllarydunmorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Amberyll Arydunmorn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1609<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(4/8/02 11:26:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=1