rap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/utorlack.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Torlack</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NWN PlayTester</span><br>  Posts: 689<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(4/8/02 12:43:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://personal.atl.bellsouth.net/atl/e/t/etssmith/bandit_thumb.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lots of Discussion on saving Variables</span><hr size=1> Actually, this is a very interesting question.<br><br>Everyone makes mistakes.  Every field of work has an acceptable level of mistakes.  Mistakes have different ramifications.<br><br>If a lawyer misspells &quot;the&quot; as &quot;teh&quot;, I would imagine no great loss.  If a lawyer misses important case law, someone might get the chair.<br><br>If a programmer makes a mistake, the UI might act odd but the software still is very usable.  If he types the wrong word in the wrong place in the code, the software might not even function at all.<br><br>If a nuclear power plant worker ....<br><br><!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Has there been studies about which lines of work are more error prone.  Do mistakes in certain lines of work tend to be more costly than others.<br><br>hmm, interesting thoughts.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showMessageRange?topicID=322.topic&start=21&stop=30>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showPrevMessage?topicID=322.topic"> <img src="http://milynna.homestead.com/files/previous.gif" border=0><